</i> must also be considered a strong possibility.","Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames.","Americanized form of German   Brucks  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Brucks","meanings":["North German:","probably a habitational name from Brucks (also Brux) which derives from Middle Low German <i>brōk</i> ‘low-lying marsh’.","reportedly also an altered form of Flemish (Dutch) <b>Broex</b>, an old variant of <b>Broeks</b> (see   Brooks  )."]},{"name":"Brook","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived by a brook, stream, water-meadows or low, marshy ground, from Middle English <i>brook</i>, Old English <i>brōc</i> ‘brook, stream’; or a habitational name from any of various places called with this word, such as Brook (Kent, Rutland) or Brooke (Norfolk).","North German: topographic name for someone who lived by a water meadow or marsh, from Low German <i>brook</i> (cognate with German   Bruch   ‘swamp’ and Old English <i>brōc</i>; see 1 above).","Americanized form of Dutch <b>Broek</b>: topographic name from <i>broek</i>, a cognate of 2 above."]},{"name":"Brookes","meanings":["English (West Midlands): variant of   Brooks  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":73,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705188,"age":82,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705189,"age":117,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs William BROOKS was born about 1142, in England. She married William BROOKS about 1160, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1142–":"umbes 1142–Surnud","1140–Male":"1140–Surnud","1165–Male":"1165–Surnud","1142–Female":"1142–Surnud","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","Abt 1165":"umbes 1165","1165":"1165","1142":"1142","1140":"1140","about 1142":"umbes 1142","ABT 1160":"umbes 1160","Of,,, England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Of, Oakley, Northamptonshire, England":"Oakley, Hampshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"fi":{"about 1142–":"noin 1142–Kuollut","1140–Male":"1140–Kuollut","1165–Male":"1165–Kuollut","1142–Female":"1142–Kuollut","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","Abt 1165":"noin 1165","1165":"1165","1142":"1142","1140":"1140","about 